Foodstuffs are responsible for European inflation
The main reason for the inflation rate in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistics Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the rate of interest, which it believes would favour rising commodity prices and a slight decline in unemployment.
The ECB is committed to keeping inflation below 2%, or at least close to the 2%.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a dilemma: inflation must be "dealt with" to avoid further action.
In November, Germany's inflation rate reached a 12-year high of 3.3 percent; in Spain, it climbed from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone is due to rising food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat prices rose 88% and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
In 2007 there was also a significant increase in the price of food oils and dairy products.
The world market price of crude oil rose 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
The ECB estimates that inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next three to four months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup detects a government crisis
After a long stagnation, Fidesz's support has grown significantly by the beginning of December, the first time since 2002 that the party has held the largest base camp, while the support for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
The difference between the three parties is evident in the strong determination of the opposition: more than two thirds (71%) are opposed to a fifth (20%) of voters for the MSCP.
The survey shows that MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry barrier: they represent 2% of the total population.
The number of party voters in both camps has increased by one percent.
Compared to the previous low, the general economic mood has deteriorated further - never before has the proportion of those who judge the country's economic situation as "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it "fairly bad".
After a hopeful outlook for spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about the change in their financial situation.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects further deterioration; only one tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents - a historic high - rated the prime minister's work as "rather bad than right".
Thirteen percent of respondents have high confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the share of supporters of Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Some 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% who distrust the head of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be controlled even without a change of government.
If 35% of the population voted to remain in government and head of government after the unrest last October, today that number is only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) only sees a solution in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent said they would "probably" participate, and another 20 percent would "probably" vote.
For comparison, if the parliamentary elections were held on Sunday, only 55% would "certainly" go to the polls, while another 15% would consider their participation "likely".
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the tuition fee and 84% against the hospital fee.
If the group of people who took part in the referendum were to be considered 'certainly', the proportion of those who opposed tuition, internship and hospital fees would be 81, 84 and 89%, respectively.
