In many places, disinfectants are being saved
More than a thousand infections were reported in hospitals in the past year due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not particularly beneficial for the control of infections, says the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, disinfectants are also being saved.
In the trauma department of János Hospital, a MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was found in a male patient who was admitted to hospital after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection here.
The man who was injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but soon afterwards he had to return with an MRSA infection, and an important operation could not be carried out because of the bacteria still in the patient's body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 infections from hospitals caused by multi-resistant pathogens had been reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been safely registered in hospitals, but the dark numbers are likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, which is methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat infections, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are overdosed or used improperly, the antibiotic-resistant bacteria that respond well and spread quickly in hospitals under appropriate conditions will be produced.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently dysfunctional immune systems, but also in older or low-weight patients, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, or sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA infection is not a special disease, as such incidents are part of the daily life of the hospital.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA is not present only where it is not sought.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, care workers wear rubber gloves and masks, and we have the antibiotics to treat them", says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are screened for MRSA upon admission to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is too rare
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable to curb the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients being treated and isolate MRSA infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not as common in Hungarian hospitals.
The Commission has not yet decided whether to grant a grant to the scheme.
Most cases are therefore only reported when the patient has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
The European Union has strong recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and disease patterns.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always followed by hospitals.
Among outpatients or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even less common, says Karolina Böröcz.
Savings in disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by the healthcare professionals.
This is why handwashing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by either drop infection or contact, but in home hospitals, it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, with beds almost in a row, although epidemiologically, there should be at least a distance of 1.5 metres between them.
As Karolina Böröcz notes, unfortunately, even in financially less well-off hospitals, disinfectant savings are being made, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that almost favor the emergence of infections.
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should take into account the fact that the Commission has not yet adopted a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the dangers of the use of the drug.
Government programme against MRSA
Managing MRSA infections is costing health insurance companies enormously, so they're being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment has been included in the government programme.
The programme is showing early signs of success - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
The death squad chief was not drunk.
In the case of the fatal car accident caused by the Chief of Police of the XXII District, the official report is now available.
The now retired police chief of the XXII district, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was neither drunk nor under the influence of drugs, Attila Morvai, the press spokesman for the Budapest Prosecutor General's Office, said on Friday after the official report on the case was submitted.
The report confirmed the results of the initial investigation that the police chief had not consumed alcohol before he got behind the wheel.
The former police chief drove his own car into Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII district, and overtook a 55-year-old man crossing the road at an unmarked spot.
(However, according to the StVO this is not a mild circumstance - the driver has secondary status even if pedestrians do not cross the road on the zebra strip.)
The pedestrian died of his injuries after being admitted to hospital.
According to police reports, the driver suffered a shock, resigned afterwards and asked for retirement.
The Budapest Prosecutor's Office has opened its investigation into the incident.
Moreover, Attila Morvai mentioned that the former police chief had cooperated with the investigators from the beginning.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements totalling EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday, with the money to go to education, transport and environmental infrastructure and the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework in 2006 to finance transport and environmental projects financed by grants from the Cohesion Fund.
The EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be used to finance education projects.
The EIB has granted a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for this purpose; the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the area of innovation, the contracting parties signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will be mainly used for research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
The meeting also discussed the subway line 4.
It was agreed that once Hungary had agreed with the EU the details of subway financing, the original contract and any modifications would be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary totalling EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is EURIBOR-linked and the loan is provided by the EIB with an eight-year grace period, without any provisions.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe is looking closely at the formerly seldom mentioned Balkan state.
What, where and who is buying in the EU's still cheapest market, which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought-after real estate market in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, while Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Sunshine Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar are the most popular, but properties around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will attract investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena and Triavna, and the highly favorable region of Russia will also attract more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive offers - commercial and office spaces offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf destinations in Europe, attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
Foreseeable investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria also want to change their lifestyle.
Most of the buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and ski areas.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized properties for 50 to 100 000 euros, or fallen houses for 5 to 15 000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility, as well as communication opportunities, are highly valued, but proximity to a major city, shops and doctors are also crucial for buyers.
The second category includes those looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed in December as one of the top ten German holiday destinations).
The third group is made up of businessmen who invest with the aim of medium to long-term value-adding.
However, real estate in the capital is becoming more expensive, driven by ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but over the past five years there has been a 21 per cent annual price increase.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the post-2012 international climate regime will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
There is a heated debate going on between industrial and developing countries.
The United States has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the industrialized countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on support for developing countries was also reached.
The Kyoto Protocol adaptation fund will be managed by a 16-member Council, expected to be part of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as set out in the 'Piac et profit' section.
Hungary 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for the Environment, Gábor Fodor, supports the EU's commitment to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (at 1990 levels) by 2020 regardless of whether the 'post-2012 agreement' is achieved successfully or not.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its 15 Member States at the time.
The requirement for Hungary is a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared with 1985-87 - a requirement which the country will certainly meet, as the Ministry of the Environment's press release shows.
The commitment is high on Bali - at least the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the Kyoto Protocol's reduction plans would not be followed by a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the UN's Nobel Peace Prize-winning International Committee on Climate Change in its recent report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and increase the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be inevitable, leading to extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British Army is advertising on YouTube
British Army units have posted video footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the RAF has discovered YouTube: Special Forces in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The images taken with miniature cameras mounted on helmets are checked at Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London where they are posted online.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The UK Ministry of Defence was registered as 'defenceheadquarters' in the spring of 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Commonwealth Office and the International Peace Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally published the videos to recruit soldiers, and the Department of Defense says the contributions are also intended to inform the public about the real goals of foreign operations.
This kind of propaganda is almost free of charge compared to traditional television commercials, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message as they confirm the legitimacy of the government's military measures in their own way.
Americans are advertising with play
But the army must also fight amateur footage that, in addition to the carefully edited, censored footage, also makes it online - such as those showing the deaths of soldiers: the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films talk about the losses at the highest level, but the bloody sides of war are not shown.
By the way, many videos of war in Iraq and Afghanistan have been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre".
The Americans, however, are promoting the slightly different way, namely with the free-to-download shooter game "America's Army", in which the player can sneak into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-affirming simulation.
