More and more forces are mobilized for a massive strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Federation of Trade Unions will form their coordination committee on Friday for the indefinite strike starting on Monday.
A general protest meeting will be held on Saturday, and the strike will begin on Monday, the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act.
Strike-related significant traffic congestion is expected as rail traffic is almost completely halted and Budapest public transport operators (BKV) are also on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of the strike on Monday will be announced jointly by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions on Friday afternoon.
A strike committee for the LIGA-MOSZ is also set up to coordinate the actions on Monday.
A general protest meeting will be held on Saturday and, from Monday onwards, all organisations which join the strike will cease work indefinitely unless agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike, which began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act, was not defined.
If the National Council does not approve the Health Insurance Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet to discuss further action.
The Commission has already decided to adopt a new policy on health insurance, which is to be implemented in the future.
The strike, which will begin on Monday, will have to face significant traffic obstacles: railway workers will be laid off indefinitely, most public transport will be silent in the morning and more than half of Volán's communities will be silent.
At the same time, there will be one-way traffic jams in many places.
The call for strike was followed by numerous unions and civil organisations - the list of participants is updated on the League website.
Some organisations have announced indefinite strikes, others plan temporary layoffs.
Until Thursday afternoon, no agreement on sufficient services had been reached between the Hungarian Railway MÁV and the Free Union of Railways VDSZSZ, although more and more people were travelling on the train just around Christmas.
According to reports, the BKVs are on strike from start to finish at 1 p.m. and at Budapest Airport between 7 and 9 a.m. and the LIGA electricity and heat unions are on strike for four hours.
The Hungarian Medical Association is on strike at different times nationwide, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is on strike for two hours.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and present a new concept for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
The third requirement is that eligible occupational groups be given access to the early retirement system before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which is part of the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer made by the Ministry of Transport for the sub-lines and is now demanding a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases state risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded in August with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that the highest political risk in the context of the activities of the Hungarian Guard is the "increasing of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is likely to provoke such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure by the political authorities: 'Public figures have left the discussion of Roma issues to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian opposition.'
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremists and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also considers that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the local and foreign media, "have significantly damaged Hungary's image abroad, particularly in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We recall that since autumn 2006, the reorganisation of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been on a continuous rise, so that since summer 2007, several organisations have been established calling themselves "National Self-Defense Association".
"The common thread between these groups is that they define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly boasting that they prepare their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (disaster protection, national defense, law enforcement), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself", it said.
And furthermore, all this is done according to that method which tries to disguise various political endeavours based on the political and party craziness of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on civil character and the organisation of the association is therefore not only used to overcome legal obstacles that may arise in the course of registration in court - it is also a political strategy.
As the analysis shows, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also increase the risk of developing relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, and some ultra-nationalist politicians in certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as a confirmation of their own anti-Hungarian policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region.'
The establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, and the political risk to the whole region has increased.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The Bulgarian Guard was created in the wake of the Roma mass riots in a neighbourhood of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU has taken the incidents as the basis for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the purpose of the organisation is 'national protection'.
In her opinion, in the past 17 years, there has been a real "gypsy terror" in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, Political Capital says.
And furthermore, the initiative would have sparked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As I said, the increased risk of ethnic conflict is also evidenced by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organisations have announced the establishment of their own guards for resistance purposes.
The activities of the Hungarian Guard have so far shown many similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, so it is not excluded that the Hungarian Roma will also respond to the threats by organising their own protection, says the risk warning report from Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, Director of Research at Political Capital, said at the request of the news office: "Risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
Risk analysis reports would be published annually and, should risk-changing trends be visible, public opinion would be informed, as in the case of the risk warning report.
Holidays aren't holidays everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of rearranging working days around the holidays has now become established, but we will have fewer such days in the coming year.
In the European Union and in America, too, "holiday" is understood differently.
The Hungarian legal system makes a distinction between public holidays and working days.
Public holidays are usually church holidays or associated with important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year, for example: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are days off work - the latter alone allows New Year celebrants to rest.
We have a total of fourteen holidays throughout the year.
The national holidays are March 15, which commemorates the 1848 Revolution, and October 23, the anniversary of the 1956 Revolution.
On August 20th, the founding of the state, on May 1st, the celebration of work, on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our dead.
