The integration of Slovak pupils into British schools is failing
In the UK, the number of children from Eastern European countries is increasing, which raises concerns amongst the local community about the further development of local school systems.
The integration of Eastern Europeans has thus far encountered a number of obstacles.
British schools even report cases of increased violence in the conflict between immigrants and the children of the original inhabitants.
The problem of integrating children from Eastern Europe into British schools is illustrated in the case of North Kent, where the conflicts between the local population and Slovak immigrants are gradually increasing.
Disputes, harassment and bullying among students have spread to the relationships between parents.
The situation has already developed to such an extent that the police in Chatham arrested a Slovak woman who had beaten a ten-year-old boy with an iron rod.
The defendant claimed that the boy had insulted her with racist insults.
Police also had to intervene after two minor girls attacked a Slovak immigrant.
The girls had allegedly made racist remarks and stoned the man.
"On our way home, a boy climbed a bush and spat on us.
When I told him to stop, he threw apples and pears at us and then blew his ass off", one mother of a Slovak student told The Times of another unpleasant incident.
Complaints come from both sides.
One local even described the dispute with the Eastern European immigrants as a struggle for survival.
The above cases show that the mood between locals and immigrants in British schools is becoming increasingly tense.
In the UK, 70,000 Slovaks are reported to have come here looking for work.
Some 30,000 Slovak pupils attend British schools.
