On the Caribbean islands, you can find this in abundance.
But there is only one island where you can find much more, and that island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
In the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana was once a transit camp of treasures that the Spanish had stolen from America and transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the leaders of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during Prohibition) was seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were:
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra, and all that.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, and the wide boulevards were lined with cars that were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
