For giving a teddy bear a name, she was brought to court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who was accused of insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison and deportation by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman was accused of allowing six to seven-year-old students to name a teddy bear Muhammad, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of students complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old primary school teacher who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code.
In fact, this matter began in September when the teacher asked her six- to seven-year-old pupils to choose a name for the class teddy.
"The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed", reports school principal Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all, it is also a very common first name in Sudan.
Then the children created a book for the class, with the bear's picture on it and the caption "My name is Mohammed".
The bear himself did not carry a sign with that name, but the problem is simple: the portrayal of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well, and she would never have done anything to bring her too close to religious belief, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name", and he said it was just an "innocent mistake".
An opinion shared by many of the teacher's students, who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and as "one who never talks about religion in class".
It should be noted that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common surname in the UK, with 14 different spellings in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of homage to the Prophet (often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of that first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is of course a question of interpretation.
On Wednesday, at the last meeting in Vienna, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo ended a sixth and final discussion in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning without overcoming their controversies over the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties could not reach agreement on the status", European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
In the context of the negotiations, the Commission has also called on the Member States to take the necessary measures to ensure that the peace process is fully operational.
"No violence is expected in the near future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time", he added, indicating that there are clear tensions.
End of the mediation on 10 December
The troika's mediators, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, which is 90% Albanian, could be clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Kharchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and last negotiating session since the troika was given a new mandate by the UN in August.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mandate to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked Kosovo's independence from the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that deadline.
"Russia has been and remains a supporter of a negotiated solution, a consensual solution", said Bosan-Kharchenko.
The one-sided declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration, Western countries consider EU-supervised independence the only solution with a future.
Pristina is prepared to declare them unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favour.
Belgrade is seeking greater autonomy
"Unfortunately, no agreement was reached", said Fatmir Sejdiu, the president of the Kosovo Autonomous Authority, at the Baden hotel where these 'last chance negotiations' were held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regret.
However, he added that the Belgrade-proposed autonomy plan "is part of a past that has led to murder and deportation".
The 'domino effect'
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, believed that a compromise was always to be sought and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade believes that it is particularly concerned about a "domino effect" in a region still so weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
"For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible", he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision be taken solely and exclusively by the Security Council, where their Russian ally has a veto.
"The Parliament of Kosovo will have the final say"
"Only a decision from the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia", said Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
"These negotiations took two years.
They must end up as they started: in the Security Council".
In response to reporters, Fatmir Sejdiu said that "the Kosovo Parliament will have the final say on the status", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population would be "in agreement" with the Western countries.
Bush unlocked an agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
At the opening of the international peace conference, which he led Tuesday in Annapolis, Maryland, President Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed to a joint declaration.
He further stated that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately begin negotiations to find a final settlement of the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do everything to help them reach a "peace treaty" before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must destroy "terrorist infrastructure" and Israel must stop its colonization efforts, Bush said, reminding the two sides of their commitments to the "peace roadmap" agreed in 2003.
The White House chief stressed that negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority under Abbas would ultimately seek a peace treaty that would resolve all open issues without exception, including the central ones".
This designation covers the three major issues that have been the main focus of the Israeli-Palestinian dispute: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of Arab refugees who were expelled from their homeland in the 1948 conflict in what is now the State of Israel.
Abbas, the US president, said he was speaking and insisted that the upcoming negotiations be conducted "comprehensively and thoroughly" and that a settlement be reached on all points, including Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security.
Olmert, for his part, pledged to ensure that the forthcoming ceasefire negotiations were conducted "directly and without interruption" and that he would endeavour to ensure that they could be concluded before the end of 2008.
Bush has set a deadline for the implementation of his "two-state vision", a Palestinian and an Israeli one, next to each other, by the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has disclosed that it received assurances in this sense from Bush before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a great success for Washington, has launched a plan adopted by all Arab countries that offers Israel peace in return for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
