After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents in the archive, which are located in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, have so far been unable to be viewed unless they are "humanitarian", i.e. individually and in name, at the request of a former victim or his family.
The 11 governments responsible for administering the programme - including Germany, France, Israel and the USA - agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process for this Decision has been completed, the opening has been in force since yesterday.
The Commission shall adopt delegated acts in accordance with Article 21 of this Regulation.
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will enable them to conduct research, "especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health of forced labourers", explains Reto Meistern, head of the archive, which is managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The lists of concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians who had been deported or forced to work and, if necessary, to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, a part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
"Nothing fundamental can be expected from these documents", said Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
