The Congress approves the MIFID Directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
In parallel with the parliamentary draft, which closed its session today with the Congressional resolution in the Senate on the amendments to the project, the Government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously commended the efforts of the Members of the Congress and the Senate, who in their negotiations and voting had sought to establish the best possible regulation to ensure investor safety and regulate individual business activities in order to ensure a generally efficient market.
In addition to modernising financial markets, MIFID, which re-establishes the rules on securities services, aims to improve investor protection, increase the control requirements of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive allows for the provision of financial advice to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons and also helps to set up new financial services firms (ESIS), advisory firms that partner with investment and securities brokerage firms.
It also extends the number of financial transaction systems, thus adding to regulated circulating markets the multilateral systems of effect trading and the systems of internationalization of trading orders, which would eventually compete with current economic operators.
The law requires investment firms to disclose the priorities of their business profile, the confrontation and the forms of risk management on the market and to register all the operations carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV's control function.
The Congressional Economic Commission subsequently considered further changes, with the decision that securities debt must now be considered as 'complex' financial assets due to its high risk level for the investor confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis.
The Commission also took advantage of the entry into force of the Directive on the legal limitation of the work areas of graduate economists, which was adopted 30 years after the Regulation restricting the work areas reserved for economists was adopted in 1977.
The Senate, for its part, set out new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the economic intermediary who works on a foreign account, does not require authorisation from the CNMV and can offer its services to commercialise products and to attract customers simultaneously to several investment firms.
