What insurance is best for me?
The car insurance covering any damage caused by the driver is a high cost, which in turn depends on various factors, including age, gender, date of issue of the licence, family status, type of car to be insured and use, etc.
Owning a car is just the beginning.
It is even more difficult to find the right car insurance than the right model.
First of all, you have to understand what we're dealing with here.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and an insured person.
This agreement shall be concluded in writing by means of an insurance contract which stipulates that the company shall receive the insurance premium agreed and shall in return provide the corresponding amount of compensation in the event of damage.
The insurance premium is the price of an insurance policy composed of several factors, including age, gender, date of issue of the driving licence, family status, type of vehicle to be insured or use.
Insurance companies set their prices according to the statistics, so that higher contributions are also payable in the event of a higher risk of accidents.
For this reason, both women and people over 25 have to pay less, because statistics show that these groups have a lower accident rate due to their caution.
The same applies to married persons, as they are less likely to have accidents than single persons, according to statistical data and according to the firm's belief.
The benefit attributed to the vehicle affects the frequency of driving and thus the likelihood of an accident.
The more frequent the use, the more likely the damage is.
In determining the premium, insurance companies must take into account a number of points.
For this reason, the driver must also study the situation carefully in order to choose the exact car insurance that best meets his personal needs.
We will now list the most important points to consider when choosing insurance to make a choice not only in terms of performance but also in terms of price.
Under 25s face many obstacles when choosing a low-cost insurance policy, such as low driving experience and a 'young' driving licence.
Even if it is best to take out a full-cost insurance policy for ideal insurance coverage, there are still cheaper alternatives.
The prudent drivers can choose a full-cost insurance with self-employment, so that the benefits of full-cost insurance are covered but at a low price.
This type of contract involves the customer having to pay part of the amount incurred by the damage himself.
"The amount is fixed before the contract is concluded and based on the amount of the insurance premium, which is higher the lower the amount to be paid", explains Luis Noguera, Spain's chief representative at First Europa, an online insurance intermediary.
Another option is extended insurance, which provides insurance against external accidental damage but not against damage to the car itself.
In addition, this type of insurance would cover theft, fire and vehicle loss.
I'll give you some advice.
If you are under 25, it is up to you to reduce insurance costs, so your credit will increase by trying to drive carefully and avoid accidents.
A credit is a reduction in the basic rate at the relevant insurance company.
On the contrary, a penalty payment involves an increase in the said tariffs.
The amount of loans and penalties depends on the company and its income.
If the company has a profitable year behind it, it can afford to increase the bonus payments", explains Noguera.
Once the 25-year mark is exceeded, it is easier for drivers to sign a contract, because the accident rate is decreasing as driving practice increases.
It is therefore most appropriate to opt for a full-income insurance policy with self-interest.
"Normally, young people cannot benefit from their previous experience, either in the event of an accident or at the time of driving", explains the Spanish head of the European company, adding that the majority of accidents occur in the second year of training after the 'beginner's fear' has been removed.
However, it is more appropriate for a married customer who has no children to take out full-cost insurance, of course only if the financial situation of the person concerned allows it.
The insurers consider that couples with children are the customers with the lowest accident rate and their contributions are also low.
In this case, a full-cost insurance policy with a self-interest rate of around EUR 300 would be the best option.
"They are generally more relaxed and have a greater purchasing power, which allows them to make a higher contribution", notes Luis Noguera.
It is possible for pensioners to take out a full-cost insurance with a self-interest (about EUR 150) or an extended insurance which is only used if the credit is sufficiently high.
Finally, it must be noted that car insurance is something very important, not only because it protects the driver from possible accident damage, but also because it carries high costs that require careful selection to suit our personal situation.
