New concerns about the Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
A new price dispute is raging between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian fuel exports to Western Europe being affected.
Most of Russia's natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are directed by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be charged more because the group has agreed to pay up to 50% more for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine would have to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important guest states in talks", Ukraine's economy minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine".
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a drop in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices up sharply.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own gas reserves with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS 'must check foreign workers'
The Scottish public health service must improve the controls of the pre-trial registers for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation by Chief Financial Officer Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in in connection with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish public health service has no precise estimates of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were correctly performed on a sample of five health authorities.
The Chief Financial Officer examined personnel recruited outside the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a van was driven through the doors of the main terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in Britain.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out pre-employment checks on foreign workers to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the Agency does not have jurisdiction to obtain this information outside the UK.
The Chief Auditor's report now states, among other recommendations, that the Board should adopt guidelines from the Criminal Records Exemption, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not routinely carried out", the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their research guidelines to a high degree before hiring, but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign healthcare workers is available".
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that the current NHS Scotland pre-employment tests are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide", he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign staff, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely higher, partly because the boards had trouble identifying those employees who are on indefinite leave.
The investigation further found that established control procedures were mostly followed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian.
This includes passports, work permits and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign staff in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was concerned about doing this work in view of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport".
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices are reflected in the updated guidelines on control checks ahead of the recruitment of all staff, including those from abroad, which are scheduled for publication next month.
