The climate on Venus could give us a glimpse of the future of the earth
Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from an orbiting European spacecraft shows that the planet resembles a distant twin of Earth even more than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the sun.
Billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have been very similar to those on Earth and could have even been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unbridled greenhouse effect of carbon dioxide, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation, and a slower rate of rotation, Venus took a very different course.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which studied the plants for a year, offer a sobering insight into how the earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Physics Department at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar".
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario where Venus began billions of years ago as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment".
