In 1980 and 2000, a candidate has been joining the party from the start and convincingly with a victorious message about the greatness of America and a twinkling of an eye on both wings of the party.
This time the party is divided and the outcome is far from clear.
The pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this one's not particularly sleepy.
No noble title seems to have been sold, no politician paid Paris hotel bills, no foreign toes sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has been covering up donations to the UK's ruling Labour Party for more than 650,000 pounds over four years under the name of other people, and that the party failed to report it, is something that the rival Gordon Brown would have done well without.
When the Prime Minister withdrew the call for an election two months ago, foolishly insulting British intelligence by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced this decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly shrewd Liberal Democrat chairman, put it, the Brown once feared by Stalin has evolved into Mr. Bean.
The unfortunate rescue of Northern Rock, a bank that was hit, showed weak regulatory and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have led business associations to oppose the government.
The tax authorities' loss of personal data of 25 million people showed unimaginable administrative fraud.
A trio of retired generals started a riot in the upper house protesting military spending cuts: they claimed to be minister of the armed forces, a part-time job.
Now there are the many different donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's secretary general (and its former executive director) has already resigned.
None of this means Brown is irrevocably retiring.
Yet governments can reach a turning point after which they feel it is impossible to govern.
People may not trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it becomes clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, this delay is over: the public service begins to leak; the cabinet ministers begin to chatter; the press is looking for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he wanted to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction files, for example, are related to decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's misfortune - like the long "nobility money" investigation into political party funding - voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown's situation isn't quite as bad as it looks.
The mistakes are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
Like Mr. Bean, no one died or was completely distracted.
And the countermeasure, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Browns' Stalinist tendencies of course always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new political donation trend is a good example.
The garboesque Abraham, who compares his donations to his charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his goodwill.
That may be true, but he didn't have the choice.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's agreement but didn't say it was illegal, will of course have to ask some questions, just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's chief financial officer, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far, Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these confusions, even though most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he watered that determination by seizing a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to the full measure, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lectures" are not very complicated.
If the law has been broken, it's a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things Mr Brown must do, such as find a permanent chairman of the Independent Standards Committee on Public Life, which has been vacant for six months, and move forward with a comprehensive reform of political party financing.
This would require the hardliners of Labour to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to abandon the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a party member like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in the polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can win is through undeniable integrity and solid competence.
