Is the credit crisis affecting the American credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's only natural that the spinal fluid swirls around excitedly.
Now that America's real estate market is in tatters, the predators are targeting the country's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of underfunded loans spreading to other forms of consumer credit spreads.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both borrowing and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are either unsecured or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it had withdrawn $1.4 billion in fees from its US consumer financing, partly because of weak credit card holders.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and losses are still low.
According to the Moody's rating agency, the third-quarter surge rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the US private insolvency law in 2005 led to a sharp drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn accounted for a large part of the credit card losses; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would rise again whether or not general conditions for borrowers deteriorate.
The industry also reports solid repayment rates that show how much of their debt consumers pay each month
And trust in credit card-based securities is pretty strong, despite the downturn in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research firm, expects that expenditure for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take credit card debt, now that home loans are draining.
However, card issuers look at cash flow rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be beneficial to the card exhibitors.
The incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates decrease when the property is less valuable than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among the repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond to the more volatile conditions much faster and more flexibly than lenders by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of the assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and completely reevaluate loans", says Gary Perlin, Capital One's chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden undercutting crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and a credit crunch push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a grimer future.
Keep looking for those shark fins.
British bankers plead guilty to Enron
Three British bankers who were due to face trial for their role in the fraudulent scheme with former Enron chief financial officer Andrew Fastow changed their pleas to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of wire fraud for allegedly conspiring with Fastow in a secret financial fraud in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of their employer.
The procedure had been postponed to January.
But during a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., everyone pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of the Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, were identified in the UK during two-year extradition proceedings.
In the United States, her case marks the loose end of an investigation that began after Enron's collapse in 2001.
The charges initially filed against her in 2002 made Fastow aware that he was the target of a government investigation into the Enron decline.
The indictment against the bankers, known as the "NatWest Three", claims they came to Houston in 2000 to plot a fraudulent plot with Fastow and his former top adviser Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partnership controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of countless fraudulent Enron schemes that helped drive the company into bankruptcy.
In early 2002, the bank had estimated the value of its stake in the subsidiary at zero, but the three British men knew that it was in fact of considerable value.
A company controlled by Kopper acquired the bank's shares in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely claimed to Enron that the energy company would pay Greenwich NatWest $20 million for its shares in the subsidiary.
But the 20 million dollars actually went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others were paid about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy to commit wire fraud in Enron's bankruptcy.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in the Louisiana State Penitentiary.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence at a facility in Texarkana.
Each of the three men was on parole on a $1 million bail that required them to live in the United States awaiting trial.
Enron, once the nation's seventh-largest company, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks that prevented it from covering up its billions in debt or making weak businesses appear profitable.
The collapse destroyed thousands of jobs, more than 60 billion in market value, and more than two billion dollars in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the Enron crash.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were overturned after he died of heart disease last year.
Not quite down in Moscow
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough range to fly nonstop from Moscow to Los Angeles is at least $54 million.
But that's a small sum for some of the rich Russians.
"It can accommodate up to 18 passengers", said Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of you are asking for so many seats because it's for a private family or a corporate president".
Firer was at the Gulfstream stand last Friday at the Millionaires Exhibition, a four-day showcase consumer orgy held in a nestled exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury vendors had built exhibition stands, hoping to interest newly-arrived Russians in everything from mahogany-plated yachts to diamond-coated car grills that would be appropriate for 50 cents.
Firer carefully aimed a shiny orange Porsche at the nearest stand.
"That's a nice car, but it's a small sum compared to us", he said.
"Russia is the second largest market for private aircraft after the United States".
Heated by an oil boom, the Russian capital seems as flooded with money as Dallas in its heyday.
"We went through the same period in the 1890s when some Americans came to gigantic wealth and went in crowds to Europe, where they were seen as materialistic", said Marshall Goldman, a scientist at Harvard University's Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies.
Like the Saudi Arabian airlines of the 1970s and the Japanese in the 1990s, the Russians are emerging as the world's most visible free-floating money issuers.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of the gold rush.
Elsewhere in Moscow, this week a conference of the luxury industry drew Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell high-priced goods in markets like Russia.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, which is owned by the New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires, with a total of $282 billion, according to Forbes' list of richest people.
In addition, 103,000 Russian millionaires belong to the second class, worth a combined $670 billion, according to a study on the development of private wealth in the former Soviet Union, written by economists at the Center for Economic and Financial Research, an expert group here.
(The World Bank says that in 2005, 15.8 percent of Russians lived below the poverty line.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow - that's why we're all here", said Nicole Marais, a sales and marketing representative for David Morris, a London jeweler.
She had visited the fair for the first time with the Russian retailer of the brand, the Soho Jewelry Group.
"Women are all well-groomed and men are all worth a fortune".
As they walk through the halls in evening clothes on Sunday nights, two real estate agents, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovtsova, 26, call themselves and their clients millionaires.
"I've been looking at the cars and I'm trying to decide between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche", said Mrs. Yumatova, who delivered the designer clothes she was wearing like a red carpet veteran with Joan Rivers.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at the newly rich, the type of brand-conscious Russian shoppers who would be willing to stand for hours in traffic to visit a high-end warehouse that shamelessly placed Cadillac Escalades, platinum pocket knives, Mövenpick ice cream, customized billiard tables, apartments in Dubai and teddy bears side by side.
The public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"The Russians are interested in learning which brand is the most expensive and best", said Mr. Gijrath, who was patriotically sitting at a porcelain stand of the Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft in front of a wall-sized imitation of a hand-painted blue mosaic image of Rembrandt.
"Of course, Russians are more interested in climbing climbers".
In fact, the dealers here say that the Russians with old money (which is 10 to 15 years old by Russian standards) have already moved from big-ticket logos to the kind of sober brands with limited numbers that wouldn't be marketed at a trade show.
Yet thousands of people, whether millionaires, ambassadors of millionaires or simply tourists, pushed through the halls every day.
And some of them bought.
On the first night of the show last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the general manager of King Koil Beds here, said he sold two $70,000 mattress sets made of silk, cashmere and cotton, with sewn gold threads.
Also on the first night, Mikhail Lyubiumov, a sales manager for A1 Moto, a company that supplies high-end cars with high-end alarm systems, said that his company sold the bright orange Porsche to a Russian millionaire for $170,000.
By Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a luxury car company that tailored to customer demand, said he'd sold three cooling grills for a Rolls-Royce Phantom that look like chain-linked tires for $55,000 each.
He showed a reporter a car tire designed for a Russian casino owner, with spikes he had covered with colored Swarovski crystals, so it looked like a roulette wheel.
The cost: $22,000 for a four-piece.
"The Russian millionaire who wants to have a cubic zirconium leather wheel or a picture of his wife's face will not necessarily ride on these wheels", said Mr. Karapetian.
"He'll keep it in his garage of 30 or 40 cars".
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaires" would not express much exclusivity at the moment, given the rise in local real estate prices.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash", he said.
"There are more of them than you think".
Those who were not millionaires could at least pretend to be rich at a booth run by Alliance Continental, a Russian asset management firm.
The company had set up four British-style red cell phones that were packed with tons of fake millions of dollars.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing director, said his employees had printed 500,000 fake notes for the millionaire's fair.
Passersby would stop to throw around the heaps of money, take cell phone photos while they sat back in the middle of the exchange, get picked up by friends, or just get a few million.
"You see, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire", said Mr. Karryev.
