It was embarrassing".
Hopes that the central bank will lower interest rates will lead to a rise in world stock markets
Shares jumped yesterday on both sides of the Atlantic after market hopes that the central bank would try to calm credit markets by further rate cuts were bolstered by alarming comments from the vice chairman of the US central bank.
Stock markets in London, New York and across Europe rose after Donald Kahn, the number two of Ben Bernanke, the central bank's chairman, said that policies had to be "flexible and pragmatic" to respond to the ongoing pressure on financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm volatile markets in the face of signs of rising credit tensions, Kohn said recent turbulence had "partly reversed some of the improvements in market performance from late September and October".
If the increased turbulence continues, it would increase the possibility of further tightening of financial conditions for consumers and businesses, he said.
The comments were taken up by investors as a signal that the central bank is ready to step in and stabilise credit conditions with new capital injections into US markets and possible further interest rate cuts.
The comments also helped calm Wall Street in the face of further bad news from the US economy, now that US real estate sales reached new record lows in October.
The consequences of the financial turmoil were highlighted by the announcement by Bear Stearns, the investment bank, that it will eliminate 650 jobs, or 4 percent of its global workforce, in a cost-cutting measure to offset heavy losses from its lost bets in the US mortgage lending sector.
It is expected that only 20 of these jobs will disappear in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the broader S&P 500 rose 2.65 percent.
In London, the FTSE 100 index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 6.306.2, adding more than £39 billion to the value of British stocks.
The German index Dax rose by 2.6 percent and the French CAC40 rose by 2.3 percent.
The re-emergence of credit pressure on markets had previously been highlighted after strong demand for a three-month European Central Bank guarantee auction granted to the European Commercial Banks was increased by a considerable 4.7%, the highest rate since April 2001.
The pressure on the Bank of England, the US Central Bank and the European Central Bank to follow suit and to feed more capital into the London money markets increased as credit stresses rose to their highest level since late September, following a continuous increase since 21 November, when the three-month LIBOR rate for lending between UK banks rose to 6.59%.
England faced with a decision on the statements by Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara
Here are two dilemmas, each almost as difficult as the other.
Who's going to be the number six for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, no less relevant in a broader context than the first test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is important because David Graveney, the electorate chairman, at least under this particular title, is here to help head coach Peter Moores and captain Michael Vaughan decide, and because the table of High Morries, the English chief executive, is gradually filling with applications for national electorates, if not even part-time.
Whoever doesn't get the sixth batting position will be unhappy, but life is often unfair and sports are undoubtedly.
It is never easy to pinpoint exactly what makes a person at the top of his profession, while someone else never goes beyond the lowest rank, sometimes due to lack of luck rather than ability.
It's not just cricket where selection is difficult, where judgments are needed, which are always subjective in the end.
Is this the right time for Bopara to go up?
Is it fair to Shah if he does?
The same question may be asked in another area, such as whether John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both intelligent young executives with good qualifications who know the business well, should be promoted.
Who can tell what the right class is for a cricketer unless he is given the opportunity to swim or drown?
Of course, numbers have a big influence on decisions, but so do chances.
Within a team, a cricketer must catch the captain's eye at the right time when he can take a wicket and a batsman must get regular chances on order if he wants to make an impression as a one-day cricketer.
Catching the eyes of the voters is more complicated.
There were many who were better last season than, say, James Anderson, who is apparently going to play in the first Test, even though Stephen Harmison is self-proclaimed healthy and the wind is blowing in the net.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets at 33 runs each to earn a place on this tour.
Chris Tremlett only took 29 with the same modest average, but both had their highlights and hoped for more.
Whether Shah or Bopara plays at Asgiriya Stadium can only be a matter of opinion.
The choice could decide the careers of both men, or it might make little difference.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played in every Test and was successful in the first, taking five wickets and scoring 40 useful runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, then still struggling to consolidate himself, who made the breakthrough into a major Test cricketer and who, although he scored a double century against Australia in Australia, is perhaps still underrated.
It is likely that after further discussion during today's networking session at Asgiriya Stadium, Graveney, Vaughan and Moores will follow their conservative instincts and gut feeling for Shah's greater experience of Bopara's youthful enthusiasm.
There are arguments for both.
Shah is talking about his sparkling and valuable 88 Test debut innings in Bombay, 43 first-class centuries and only six from Bopara, who is 22 years seven years younger, and an excellent balance against a round of balls.
But Shah scored just ten runs in his two innings in May against West Indies in the Lord's Test, his home ground as a Middlesex player, and this, plus his immediate rejection by the selectors as Vaughan was healthy to take his position for the next game, seems to have taken the impetus from his strike, which was still evident in Bombay.
On the contrary, the all-powerful man from Essex is a man of great joy.
He is impressed by nothing on a cricket pitch and his attitude away from it was brought to a point when he had recently overtaken a four-wheel drive vehicle at an exhibition for England's sponsor Volkswagen.
He suffered minor injuries and probably a shock, but the first thing he did was to get his Vodafone (of course, also sponsored) and call his teammate Alastair Cook, who had been watching this from a distance, and say enthusiastically, "Did you see that?"
Bopara is a much better pitcher, he's been bouncing his midfield pace with some effect here on the pitches, which seems to suit him and he's beating with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right man is one thing, choosing the right time is another.
Maybe that's the real art of choice.
I tend to give Bopara his chance now, which doesn't mean that Shah might not be doing well, if, as the tea bag from Ceylon suggests, he's the one who's playing here this weekend.
Buses take refugees back to work and fight al-Qaeda
The first busloads of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, with a stream of displaced people whose funds or visas had run out, and others hoping the city would return to normal.
Some even returned to fight the rebels they had driven out of their homes.
At Mansour Bus Station, even before 800 people from Damascus arrived in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was in operation with refugees from Syria and Jordan returning on private transport.
"I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad", said Sabah Al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on television and what I read in the newspaper about what happened in Baghdad and how it would be safe now".
They say that the Mahdi army has stopped killing people", he said, referring to the Shiite militias of militant cleric Moqtada Al-Sadr, who has ordered his forces to withdraw at this time.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher from the predominantly Sunni part of Amariyah, returned with his two children because he could not renew his Syrian visa and because the Iraqi regime did not allow him to work.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him to tell him that a local militia supported by the US had helped drive Al Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital and urged him to return.
One of the newcomers from Jordan was the leader of a Sunni and Shiite tribe who had been driven from his home in Sleikh, north of Baghdad, by a hand grenade attack after he urged his fellow citizens to fight al-Qaida.
He came back to fight.
"Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they were starting an anti-Al Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my boys.
That is why I came back today", said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they had been lured by the increasing calm in the capital since the US troop increase and the growth of local "affected citizen groups" armed and working with the US military to defend their neighborhoods.
But more people spoke of being forced home by visa problems and a lack of funds in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis had fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, expressed the general suspicion among the exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, had asked the Syrian government to impose visa restrictions on the refugees in order to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people have probably fled the sectarian death squads in the country.
"We were doing well until al-Maliki visited Syria and the government pressured the Iraqis to stop issuing visas to force them to return to Iraq", said the Sunni pensioner.
"I cannot trust a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house after I left".
Part of the reason for the decline in violence is that Sunnis have been driven out of Shia areas and vice versa, which has led to the creation of many places where tensions have eased.
There are fears that a sudden influx of refugees will reignite sectarian tensions and create conflict.
Small Saarland, good education
The smallest German state is a leader in vocational education and even has a great international orientation.
In one field of education alone, the Saarland is in the same deficit as the rest of the country.
"I declared yesterday for the 50th time to a non-Saarland that we are not French" - this slogan is self-ironically posted by the smallest federal state on its 50th birthday.
France and Luxembourg play a major role in the Saarland education system, which is ranked fifth in the Cologne Institute of the German Economy (IW) education monitor.
The European Union has a long tradition of cooperating closely with its neighbours.
The University of Saarbrücken was founded in 1948 by the French.
To this day, students can complete their studies here with a double or even triple diploma.
Accordingly, the proportion of foreign students is 15.6 percent.
But rural children also bring the Saarland to higher education in higher numbers than the average - many of them without a high school diploma.
"The Saarland vocational education system is used", says Axel Plünnecke, education expert at the IW.
More than one in five young people acquires their education at a vocational school, making Saarland more than seven percentage points higher than the federal average.
The combined possibilities of vocational and academic training are also relatively wide.
In terms of population, dual degree programmes are the second best in Germany.
However, despite the close training and increasing demand, the number of engineering graduates has fallen by a third in recent years.
The Saarland Ministry of Education has therefore now committed the universities to a marketing campaign for engineering subjects.
"We have started several reforms in the education system after the first Pisa study", says a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Education.
So the government introduced nationwide comparison tests.
To help children start learning early, the last Kita year is free of charge - a model that is now being copied by other federal states.
The results of the studies will be published in the Official Journal of the European Union.
In Pisa 2003, the proportion of at-risk students fell from 29 percent to 20 percent.
Overall, however, the Saarland did not rise as strongly as other federal states.
The Bavarians are better off.
And to the dismay of the Saarlanders, foreign language skills are not measured at Pisa - in this area you could score points.
Because the language of the neighbors is compulsory in high schools - even if the Saarlanders are not French.
