Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is thought to be more similar to Earth than it has been before: the European spacecraft Venus Express has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind gusts at the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that there is a flash on Venus.
Now the European probe Venus Express has shown that it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus is shooting at a height of about 35 miles [56 km] from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the science journal Nature.
According to the famous "soup theory", lightning caused life on earth: storms are said to have triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the Devil's twin of the Earth, but she is a twin", said Russell.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has taken such a completely different course is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as no spacecraft has been on the road to explore this planet since the early 1990s.
The researchers believe that the latest research, now presented in several Nature articles, not only highlights the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that our neighboring planet has more in common with Earth than was originally thought", says the ESA.
In addition to the already known North Pole wind, the researchers also found a cloud-shaped swirl at the South Pole, which is turning much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the earth's winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-largest planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost as large as Earth, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also called the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it rotates much more slowly around itself: a day on Venus takes 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with a surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
On both of them, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide on Earth is fixed in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
