Currently, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's worksheet.
Most of the 94 brillo boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo boxes a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now yields a sobering result: The six "Brillo boxes" that the former museum director Pontus Hultén left to the Moderna Museet in 1995 are copies - and probably most of the approximately one hundred other "Type Stockholm" Brillo boxes in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is entwined, a confusing intertwining of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York City, painted wooden boxes based on the red, blue, and white design of the "Brillo" soap powder cardboard boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - displayed hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo cartonage factory.
It was not a work of art, but a model of art, a mere exhibition.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few wooden brillo boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which were then authorized as original Andy Warhol briallo boxes, entitled "Stockholm type", and have rightly entered the history of art and auction.
Some of them have made over $100,000 at auctions.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that about a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three Swedish-owned brillo boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press pan with a paint roll without grounding - and it is not oil, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's brillo boxes", says Moderna Museet Director Lars Nittve. "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York reaches a different conclusion, the Moderna Museum will classify the six boxes in its collection as copy/exhibition material".
